passages.text: Updated model w/ unchanged '25 AFFO, lower '26

We updated our O model after its earnings print, and we made minor changes to out- year numbers. Our 2025 AFFO/share estimate is unchanged at \(54.26 (+1.8\%\) y/y), which is in line with Bloomberg consensus at\) 4.26 and the guidance midpoint (range of \(4.24 - 4.28\) ). As we think about 2H and the full year, we have about \(0.02 of bad debts incorporated into our guidance in 2H, and we are being a little conservative on a few other line items (op ex leakage, taxes). As a result, we can envision a path for O to potentially come in toward the high end of its range this year if a few things work in its favor, but we don't think there is much room at this point for the range to move up in a material way, even with sizable deal flow and also having come off a slightly softer 2Q.

Our 2026 AFFO/share estimate is down to \(4.41 (versus\) 4.43 previously and implies \(+3.5\%\) y/y), which remains higher than Bloomberg consensus of \(4.38 (+2.8\%\) y/y). Our 2027 AFFO/share is \(4.54 (versus\) 4.52 previously and implies \(+3\%\) y/y) and sits above Bloomberg consensus of \(4.50 (+2.7\%\) y/y).

On the investment side, for 2H 2025 we project \(2.5 billion in acquisitions at a 7\%\) cash yield. For 2026 and 2027, we assume acquisitions spending of \(4 billion in each year at 7\%\) cash yields. We assume balance sheet leverage from 2025- 2027 averages about \(5.4x net debt to EBITDA. Overall, we think it will be important for O to demonstrate into 2026 and beyond that it can convert its internal growth, free cash flow generation, and sizable deal volume to bottom- line earnings growth of at least 3\%. We think that will be the bar for it and peers. We sit slightly above that the next couple of years, while the Street is slightly below.

Assuming a \(7.1\%\) blended cap rate, we arrive at our NAV/share estimate of \(\) 50.85\(for O. At its current stock price, we calculate an implied cap rate of\) 6.4\% \(. Using our DCF model (2.5\% long - term AFFO growth rate, 95\% payout ratio, 9\% equity discount rate), we are establishing a Dec 2026 price target of\) \ \(62\) /share (vs. \(\) 62/ share previously for Dec 2025).

We rate shares of O Neutral. The company has significant investment reach by geography and property type in the net lease space. This should allow it significant access to deal flow as it essentially becomes a scale capital provider vis- à- vis real estate, and the company also benefits from lower capital costs compared to many of its peers. These factors should allow the company to drive consistent external growth over time on top of modest internal growth. A pushback point for the story is that its size could make growth harder to come by given ever- increasing deal activity needed to "move the needle." The company is moving into new facets of business, including being an investment manager by bringing in third- party investors into a fund vehicle, and it is also more active in purchasing multi- tenant shopping centers in Europe. While these should help add growth, we do think the jury is still out on whether the added complexity will be worth it for investors. Our Neutral rating stems from our preference for other names across our coverage.

O trades at 13.7x our 2025 adjusted FFO (AFFO) estimate vs. the net lease group average of 13.4x. Excluding the impact of leverage, we calculate that O trades at 16.7x EV/EBITDA vs. the net lease group average of 16.6x. The company has historically traded at a sizable premium to its peers.

We rate shares of O Neutral. The company has significant investment reach by geography and property type in the net lease space. This should allow it significant access to deal flow as it essentially becomes a scale capital provider vis- à- vis real estate, and the company also benefits from lower capital costs compared to many of its peers. These factors should allow the company to drive consistent external growth over time on top of modest internal growth. A pushback point for the story is that its size could make growth harder to come by given ever- increasing deal activity needed to "move the needle." The company is moving into new facets of business, including being an investment manager by bringing in third- party investors into a fund vehicle, and it is also more active in purchasing multi- tenant shopping centers in Europe. While these should help add growth, we do think the jury is still out on whether the added complexity will be worth it for investors. Our Neutral rating stems from our preference for other names across our coverage.

O trades at \(13.7x\) our 2025 adjusted FFO (AFFO) estimate vs. the net lease group average of \(13.4x\) . Excluding the impact of leverage, we calculate that O trades at \(16.7x\) EV/EBITDA vs. the net lease group average of \(16.6x\) . The company has historically traded at a sizable premium to its peers.

We are establishing a Dec 2026 price target of \(62 / 2\) share (vs. our Dec 2025 price target of \(62 / 2\) share), which is based on our DCF model. As a proxy for "cash flow," we utilize estimated dividends from our earnings model through 2031 and then assume a long- term AFFO payout beyond 2031 of \(95\%\) and \(2.5\%\) long- term AFFO growth; note that the AFFO used in our valuation differs from company- defined AFFO as our figure incorporates costs associated with originating debt and stock compensation. Our \(2.5\%\) long- term growth rate is a combination of \(1\%\) same- store NOI growth, leveraged to \(1.5\%\) AFFO growth, and an additional \(1 - 1.5\%\) AFFO growth from investments, offset marginally by some G&A growth over time. Our discount rate assumption is \(9.0\%\) after considering a range of \(8 - 12\%\) for most of the REITs in our coverage universe.
